<li>Shingleton, Bradley, 2008, &ldquo;In Search of Common Ground: The
Role of a Global Ethic in Inter-Religious Dialogue&rdquo;,
<em>Carnegie Ethics Online</em>, Carnegie Council for Ethics in
International Affairs.
 [<a href="https://www.carnegiecouncil.org/media/series/ethics-online/in-search-of-common-ground-the-role-of-a-global-ethic-in-inter-religious-dialogue" target="other">Shingleton 2008 available online</a>]</li>
 
<li>Silver, Daniel, 2001, &ldquo;Religious Experience and the Facts of
Pluralism&rdquo;, <em>International Journal for the Philosophy of
Religion</em>, 49: 1&ndash;17.</li>

<li>Skrefsrud, Trygve-Alexander, 2023, &ldquo;Rethinking the
intercultural potential of religious education in public schools:
Contributions from intercultural theology&rdquo;, <em>Religions</em>,
14(2): 224. doi:10.3390/rel14020224</li>

<li>Stott, John, and David Edwards, 1988, <em>Essentials: A
Liberal-Evangelical Dialogue</em>, London: Hodder.</li>

<li>Stenmark, Mikael, 2024, &ldquo;Choosing a Worldview&rdquo;,
<em>AGATHEOS &ndash; European Journal for Philosophy of Religion</em>,
1: 42&ndash;62.</li>

<li>Taliman, Valerie, 1993, &ldquo;Lakota Declaration of War&rdquo;,
<em>News from Indian Country</em>, 7(13): 10.</li>

<li>Tappin, Ben, Leslie van der Leer, and Ryan McKay, 2017, &ldquo;The
Heart Trumps the Head: Desirability Bias in Political Belief
Revision&rdquo;, <em>Journal of Experimental Psychology</em>, General
146: 1143&ndash;1149.</li>

<li>Tavris, Carol, and Elliot Aronson, 2007, <em>Mistakes Were Made
(But Not by Me): Why We Justify Foolish Beliefs, Bad Decisions, and
Hurtful Acts</em>, New York: Harcourt, 2007.</li>

<li>Tinklenberg, Jessica (ed.), 2020, <em>Empathy and the religious
studies classroom: Spotlight on Teaching</em> (<em>Religious Studies
News</em>, January 2020), American Academy of Religion.</li>

<li>Walls, Jerry, 2015, <em>Heaven, Hell, and Purgatory: Rethinking
the Things that Matter Most</em>, Grand Rapids, MI: Brazos Press.</li>

<li>Wuthnow, Robert, 2005<em>, America and the Challenge of Religious
Diversity</em>, Princeton: Princeton University Press.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Other Important Works</h3>

<ul class="hanging">

<li>Ahmad, Saiyad F., and Ahmad, Saiyad S., 2004, <em>God, Islam, and
the Skeptic Mind: A Study on Faith, Religious Diversity, Ethics, and
the Problem of Evil</em>, 2nd edition, Berlin: Blue Nile
Publishing.</li>

<li>Aijaz, Imran, 2014, &ldquo;Traditional Islamic Exclusivism: A
Critique&rdquo;, <em>European Journal for the Philosophy of
Religion</em>, 6: 185&ndash;209.</li>

<li>Anderson, Pamela, 2011, &ldquo;A Feminist Perspective&rdquo;, in
Chad Meister (ed.), <em>The Oxford Handbook of Religious
Diversity</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press, pp.
405&ndash;420.</li>

<li>Baker-Hytch, Mathew, 2014, &ldquo;Religious Diversity and
Epistemic Luck&rdquo;, <em>International Journal for Philosophyof
Religion</em>, 76: 171&ndash;191.</li>

<li>Cheng, Chung-Ying, 2011, &ldquo;A Chinese Religions
Perspective&rdquo;, in <em>The Oxford Handbook of Religious
Diversity</em>, Chad Meister (ed.), Oxford: Oxford University Press,
pp. 351&ndash;364.</li>

<li>Christenson, David, 2009, &ldquo;Disagreement as Evidence: The
Epistemology of Controversy&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy Compass</em>, 5:
756 &ndash;767.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2016, &ldquo;Conciliation, Uniqueness, and
Rational Toxicity&rdquo;, <em>No&ucirc;s</em>, 50: 584&ndash;603</li>

<li>Craig, William Lane, 2008, &ldquo;Is Uncertainty a Sound
Foundation for Religious Tolerance?&rdquo; in <em>Religious Tolerance
Through Epistemic Humility: Thinking With Philip Quinn</em>, J. James
Kraft and D. David Basinger, (eds.), Burlington, VT: Ashgate
Publishing Company, pp. 13&ndash;28</li>

<li>Dastmalchian, Amir, 2013, &ldquo;The Epistemology of Religious
Diversity in Contemporary Philosophy of Religion&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophy Compass</em>, 8: 298&ndash;308.</li>

<li>De Cruz, Helen, 2019, <em>Religious Disagreement</em> (Cambridge
Elements Philosophy of Religion), Cambridge: Cambridge University
Press.</li>

<li>Feldman, Richard, 2006, &ldquo;Epistemological Puzzles About
Disagreement&rdquo;, in <em>Epistemology Futures</em>, Stephen
Hetherington (ed.), Oxford: Oxford University Press, pp.
216&ndash;236.</li>

<li>Feldman, Richard$$ and Ted Warfield, 2010, <em>Disagreement</em>,
Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Griffin, David, 2014, &ldquo;Deep Religious Pluralism&rdquo;, in
<em>The Blackwell Companion to Religious Diversity</em>, Kevin
Schilbrack (ed.), Oxford: Wiley-Blackwell, pp. 73&ndash;88.</li>

<li>Harrison, Victoria, 2015, &ldquo;Religious Pluralism&rdquo;, in
<em>The Routledge Handbook of Contemporary Philosophy of
Religion</em>, Graham Oppy (ed.), London and New York: Routledge, pp.
257&ndash;269.</li>

<li>Hick, John, 1980, <em>God Has Many Names</em>, London: Macmillan
Press, Ltd.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1985, <em>Problems of Religious
Pluralism</em>, New York: St. Martin&rsquo;s Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1997a, &ldquo;The Epistemological Challenge
of Religious Pluralism&rdquo;, <em>Faith and Philosophy</em>, 14:
277&ndash;286.</li>

<li>Himma, Kenneth, 2002, &ldquo;Finding a High Road: The Moral Case
for Salvific Pluralism&rdquo;, <em>International Journal for
Philosophy of Religion</em>, 52: 1&ndash;33.</li>

<li>Kraft, James, 2006, &ldquo;Philip Quinn&rsquo;s Contribution to
the Epistemic Challenge of Religious Diversity&rdquo;, <em>Religious
Studies</em>, 42: 453&ndash;465.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2011, <em>The Epistemology of Religious
Disagreement: A Better Understanding</em>, London: Palgrave Macmillan,
chapter 4.</li>

<li>Kelly, Thomas, 2005, &ldquo;The Epistemic Significance of
Disagreement&rdquo;, in <em>Oxford Studies in Epistemology</em>, Tamar
Szabo Gendler and John Hawthorne (eds.), Oxford: Clarendon Press, pp.
167&ndash;196.</li>

<li>Lackey, Jennifer, 2018, &ldquo;Experts and Peer
Disagreement&rdquo;, in <em>Knowledge, Belief, and God: New Insights
in Religious Epistemology</em>, Matthew Benton, John Hawthorne, and
Dani Rabinowitz (eds.), Oxford: Oxford University Press, pp.
228&ndash; 245.</li>

<li>Lamptey, Jerusha, 2014, <em>Never Wholly Other: A Muslim Theology
of Religious Pluralism</em>, Oxford: Oxford Press.</li>

<li>Legenhausen, Mohammad, 2005, &ldquo;A Muslim&rsquo;s Non-Reductive
Religious Pluralism&rdquo;, in <em>Islam and Global Dialogue:
Religious Pluralism and the Pursuit of Peace</em>, Roger Boase (ed.),
Surrey: Ashgate, pp. 51&ndash;75.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2009, &ldquo;On the Plurality of Religious
Pluralisms&rdquo;, <em>International Journal of Hekmat</em>, 1
(Autumn): 6&ndash;42.</li>

<li>McKim, Robert, 2008, &ldquo;A Path to (and beyond)
Tolerance&rdquo;, in <em>Religious Tolerance Through Epistemic
